Wash and dry all produce. Bring a #large pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}. Mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}. Peel and mince @ginger{1%thumb}. Whisk together @sesame oil{1%tablespoon}, @ketchup{1%tablespoon}, @soy sauce{4%tablespoon}, @hoisin sauce{1%jar}, and @water{1%tablespoon} in a #small bowl{}.

Add @broccoli florets{8%ounce} to boiling water and cook until tender but still crisp, ~{3-4%minutes}. Drain and rinse under cold water. Set aside.

Toss @beef sirloin tips{12%ounce} with @cornstarch{1%tablespoon} in a #large bowl{}. Season generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{4%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Toss in steak tips and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove and set aside.

> If you have a nonstick pan, break it out.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium heat. Add garlic, ginger, and scallions and cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}, tossing. Toss in half the @yakisoba noodles{16%ounce} from the package (we sent more) and a drizzle of oil. Break up noodles until they no longer stick together, using #tongs{} or two #wooden spoons{}.

Pour in @water{1%cup}, cover, and steam until noodles are tender, ~{3%minutes}. Uncover, increase heat to medium-high, and toss until noodles are tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add sauce and toss to coat. Cook until sauce is thickened, ~{1%minute}.

> If your pan doesn't have a lid, carefully cover it with aluminum foil.

Toss broccoli and steak into noodles to warm through. Season with as much @sriracha{1%teaspoon} as you like (careful, it's spicy). Season with salt and pepper. Divide between plates and serve.